title: The Riddle of the Sands
author: Childers, Erskine
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This must be the first book I’ve read by an author who was later executed by firing squad.The Riddle of the Sands is an early spy/adventure thriller. This must be the first book I’ve read by an author who was later executed by firing squad.The Riddle of the Sands is an early spy/adventure thriller. Set before WWI, the plot largely follows two English gentlemen cruising near the Frisian Islands on a small yacht. They suspect a German plot to wage war against England and try to uncover proof, leading them into both adventure and intrigue.Two men on a boat seems a simple premise, but there is nothing simple about this book. The writing is excellent; the detailed descriptions of sailing instantly clue the reader in to the expertise of the author in this area. His knowledge of the Frisian Islands and the general area is extensive, adding to the verisimilitude of the story. In fact, it turns out Childers even did some gun smuggling in his life (not the reason he faced the firing squad). Add to that well-drawn characters, some breathless moments and excellent audiobook narration by Anton Lesser and I was spellbound. I know it won’t be everyone’s cup of tea, but I can absolutely see why it’s considered a classic. ...more

title: The Island of Dr. Moreau
author: Wells, H.G.
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Once again, I find myself incredibly impressed by Wells. Not only was he a great thinker, he was a man of conscience and socially progressive in ways Once again, I find myself incredibly impressed by Wells. Not only was he a great thinker, he was a man of conscience and socially progressive in ways that were so far ahead of his time.The story is about a castaway, Prendrick, who is stuck on an island with a shunned scientist and his companion. When he discovers the nature of their scientific endeavours and comes face to face with some of Doctor Moreau’s previous experiments he is horrified. This is similar to Frankenstein. It’s man using science to create man with disastrous consequences, but it also draws a line between men and beasts. It’s about how easily the rules used to govern society, when toppled, lead men to revert to their baser (more beastly) natures. With the animal cruelty depicted here, it doesn’t take a lot of reflection to agree that men are the real beasts.As usual, Well’s writing has echo points far into the future. Despite this being written in 1895, long before WWII, it made me think of the concentration camps and the atrocities committed there in the name of science. And more recently, cloning and the ethics debate associated with it.After reading this book, I stumbled across an early foreword written by Wells. In it he states the book was written in response to the ‘scandalous trial’ of Oscar Wilde, which he referred to as ‘the graceless and pitiful downfall of a man of genius’. So, in addition to what I said about Wells at the start of this , he was also a brave, caring and awesome human being....more

review: This Sci-Fi classic is so impressive. Published in the 1890s, it was one of the first alien invasion stories. H G Wells was clearly an amazing thinkerThis Sci-Fi classic is so impressive. Published in the 1890s, it was one of the first alien invasion stories. H G Wells was clearly an amazing thinker with great insight into human behaviour in times of extreme hardship. I read somewhere that there was panic when the radio play version of this story first aired as people believed there was a Martian invasion taking place.The first person narration worked well to explore the novel’s themes of religion, colonialism and social Darwinism. Wells has a solid dig at British imperialism not just in the text of the book, but also in the title (‘World’ in Earth’s case being London and surrounds). Clearly he wanted to provoke thought at the time with his choice of setting. I got a distinct flavour of let’s see how you would like being invaded. At first I thought the ending softened his stance, but decided it was more prophetic about how he envisaged the ultimate outcome.I’m glad I finally got around to reading it....more

review: I wanted to like this more, the basic idea for the story was great, I just wish it had been executed differently. I think it might have been stronger I wanted to like this more, the basic idea for the story was great, I just wish it had been executed differently. I think it might have been stronger if some things had been revealed to readers earlier, rather than going for big shocking reveals, which were more meh than shocking.The repetition of some phrases was overdone. Especially when they were patently not what was going on. There was a real logic break that Kiva had been in prison for 10 years and her family keeps sending messages that they are coming. It’s been 10 years . . . Because of the way it was written, Kiva made choices that seemed really stupid at the time. And some of the plot points felt convenient rather than organic. Kiva’s assumptions around the water task had me rolling my eyes they were so obviously wrong. And the trials felt like an idea borrowed from Feyre’s trials in ACOTAR.The ending left me liking Kiva a lot less. I’m not a fan of narratives that attempt to manipulate readers and it seems obvious where this is going, so I don’t think I’ll read on. ...more

review: The big ending for book two of the Crescent City series did not make up for the rest of the book. And I'll be so disappointed if it leads to a cheesy The big ending for book two of the Crescent City series did not make up for the rest of the book. And I'll be so disappointed if it leads to a cheesy cameo.It felt like the plot seams were really showing in this book and some of them were coming apart. In particular, character motivations seemed to be flimsy at best. Let's all risk our lives for a kid we don't know because he's a kid. Let's get involved in things that turned out badly for us before because some guy we don't trust says we should. A whole lot of actions taken by characters in this book weren't underpinned by strong enough motivations. And Hunt doesn't put up nearly enough resistance as events unfold. It simply wasn't believable. Nor were some of his interactions with the new archangel, which seemed really out of character. The sex scenes had hardly any romance or chemistry involved. I started thinking, not again, whenever they cropped up. And seriously, how many more new plot points can Danika drive from the bone quarter? The Danika revelations just keep coming. For most of this book, I felt like I was watching a game of chess where there was little strategy. Pieces were being moved just so we could get to where we were supposed to end up. I'm keeping my fingers crossed that the next book hangs together better....more

review: This is an enjoyable feel-good romance.Evie, who runs a service dog company, meets up with Jake whose daughter Sam has recently been diagnosed with epThis is an enjoyable feel-good romance.Evie, who runs a service dog company, meets up with Jake whose daughter Sam has recently been diagnosed with epilepsy. Their first meeting doesn't go according to plan for anyone. Any spark of attraction is quickly extinguished when the meeting ends in insults and rudeness. Then Jake has a change of heart about getting Sam a service dog and has to reconnect with Evie . . . Evie and Jake are both likeable characters and I felt myself grinning at their interactions so many times throughout this book. They are both so adorable. And I loved, or loved to hate, so many of the other characters in this story: the clever (and cute) dogs, cheeky sisters, a nasty manipulative mum, an equally manipulative (but in a good way) pseudo mum, a piece-of-work ex-wife and a sleazy lawyer who won't take no for an answer. Add to this a truckload of baggage to sort through and the story never dragged. This is the second Sarah Adams book I've read, but it won't be my last. Next time I'll start reading earlier in the day, so I don't end up staying up half the night!...more

review: This is my least favourite book in this series. I adored the first book and really liked the second book, but this one felt flat in comparison. The maThis is my least favourite book in this series. I adored the first book and really liked the second book, but this one felt flat in comparison. The magic of the first two books for me stemmed from El’s character and then the interactions between El and Orion, but the plot of this book didn’t allow for the same magic. I also missed the setting/character of the Scholomance, which didn’t feature much in this book.So much time was spent on setting up the logic of the ending that it totally dragged in parts. There were new developments in terms of relationships that I didn’t think were necessary and seemed wrong. It actually felt like they were being dropped in to tick some box, ie tokenism, but they felt like a betrayal. The ultimate villain was revealed, and I was looking forward to a big, tension-filled ending, but they didn’t really embrace their villainy to the full so it fizzled.I still enjoyed the series, and I’d still recommend it, but this book was missing the thing that made the earlier books special and so much fun to read....more
